pullRequest.body:
The main definition is a continuous map `transCM` on pairs of compatible continuous maps from the intervals `Icc a b` and `Icc b c` to form a continuous map on `Icc a c`.

---
- [x] depends on: #18695

I'm not sure about the naming, I hesitated between `trans` to match `Path.trans` (which I eventualy chose), `concat` and `append` and am attached to neither.

@YaelDillies maybe I misunderstood your suggestion... I added a local instance for `OrderBot (Icc a b)` to clean up the left / right values, but that means that now there is a `[Fact (a \le b)]` variable covering the whole file. Which makes sense to me but might well be a terrible idea.

> @YaelDillies maybe I misunderstood your suggestion... I added a local instance for `OrderBot (Icc a b)` to clean up the left / right values, but that means that now there is a `[Fact (a \le b)]` variable covering the whole file. Which makes sense to me but might well be a terrible idea.

You interpreted my suggestion correctly. I think it makes sense here to have this Fact
Is there a reason why `Set.Icc.boundedOrder` is not an instance?
Currently it takes in `a \le b`. If it took, `Fact (a \le b)`, it should be made an instance

Would it make sense to add that instance (taking a `Fact`) to it (and the ordertop / orderbot ones) as part of this PR, to remove the need for the local instance here? As it is, any file that wants to use `concatCM` needs its own local instance just to state the assumptions...

> Would it make sense to add that instance (taking a `Fact`) to it (and the ordertop / orderbot ones) as part of this PR, to remove the need for the local instance here?

It would make sense, but as a separate PR please üôè (and request my review so that it goes in quickly)

Is this not
```suggestion
def leftval (hab : a ‚â§ b) (f : C(Icc a b, E)) : E := f ‚ä•
```
once you have made `Set.Icc.orderBot` a local instance? Do you think we need it as a separate definition?
OK it is simpler like you say, definition not needed.
And then these become the evaluation map at `‚ä•` and `‚ä§`, so probably also not worth having as separate definitions
Right.
Don't you want to also provide a junk value when `b ‚àâ Icc a b`? Then you wouldn't need `(h : b ‚àà Icc a c)`

That could be an option, but with the whole `Set.Icc.OrderBot` local instance change from above I end up carrying around `[Fact (a \le b)]` and `[Fact (b \le c)]` instead anyway. Besides, choosing a junk value seems to be slightly nontrivial (unless one adds `[Inhabited E]` or something)?
Is this called `trans` because you are transitively going from `a` to `c` by passing through `b`? I would have called that `concat`
I initially called it `concat` but then wanted to match the naming of `Path.trans`. Will rename to `concat`...

We don't indent docstrings
```suggestion
functions on the common bound do not agree, this is defined as an arbitrarily chosen constant
map. See `transCM` for the corresponding map on the subtype of compatible function pairs. -/
```
OK.

```suggestion
  toFun := Set.inclusion sorry
```
I think these should be defined in terms of the apparently missing `ContinuousMap.inclusion`
I added `ContinuousMap.inclusion`
Those two should be camel case

```suggestion
theorem concat_comp_subintervalRight (hb : f ‚ä§ = g ‚ä•) :
    (concat f g).comp subintervalRight = g := by
```
OK that makes sense. I am only using that lemma for rewrites in the direction I had, but the simp direction is the one you are suggesting.

```suggestion
  obtain rfl | hxb := eq_or_ne x b
  ¬∑ 
```
OK.
Are you sure no one will ever need the other `Ixx` versions? I wonder whether `Icc` should appear anywhere in the name
`IccInclusionLeft` then?

Intresting spelling
```suggestion
/-- The concatenation of compatible pairs of continuous maps on adjacent intervals, defined as a
```
